        Of course network gossip would reach them. Of course Florence's lie would become ammunition for plants who already hate us.

        Holloway asks — "Did they say when they'll attack?"

        Velvet says — "Soon. They're organized, coordinated, confident. This isn't posturing anymore. They intend to drive us out or destroy the facility."

        I say — "With Kira inside."

        Runner says — "They didn't specify what happens to you — but yes, they don't seem concerned about your survival."

        Scout presses against my leg — worry, fear, determination to protect.

        Holloway says — "Right. We defend. Everyone to positions—"

        Remedy interrupts — "What positions? We haven't established defensive positions."

        Holloway says — "Then we establish them now! Remedy, you take the western approach with chemical deterrents. Runner, underground networks — monitor root intrusions. Velvet — reinforce structural weak points. I'll coordinate from central position and—"

        I say — "That's not a strategy — that's just telling people to do vaguely defensive things in different directions."

        Holloway's fruiting bodies droop slightly.

        Holloway asks — "Do you have a better idea?"

        I say — "Florence would."

        Multiple plants react negatively: Runner's vines tighten, Remedy's edges contract, even Velvet makes a disapproving rustle.

        Holloway says — "Florence is not part of this group's defense planning."

        I argue — "Florence is the only one who knows tactical defense! You're all amazing at your specialties, but none of you think like this. You need someone who can coordinate defensive strategy — not just coordinate people doing defensive things."

        Holloway insists — "We can figure it out."

        I ask — "Can we? Because the hostile plants are organized and coordinated and have a plan. And we have 'everyone stand near different walls and hope for the best.'"

        Runner says — "Kira, Florence broke our trust. Working with her after that deception—"

        I interrupt — "We're about to be attacked! By plants who want to drive us out or destroy the facility! With me inside! This isn't the time for hurt feelings!"

        Holloway says — "It's not about hurt feelings — it's about whether we can trust Florence's guidance when she's proven she'll lie to us."

        I remind them — "The guidance was *GOOD*. You admitted that yourself. The source was false but the content was sound."

        Remedy says — "We don't need her. We can defend ourselves."

        I ask — "Can you? Honestly?"

        Nobody answers — they don't know. They _want_ to believe they can defend themselves without Florence, but they're not confident.

        ¶

        I say — "I'm going to ask her for help."

        Holloway starts — "Kira—"

        I interrupt — "You can stay mad at her after we survive — right now, we need her tactical thinking, and I'm going to ask her to provide it. You can choose whether to listen to her advice or not. But I'm asking."
      </text>
