        Scout bounces in emphatic agreement — they're Team Ask Florence, apparently.

        I head toward the far wing before anyone can stop me.
        Holloway calls after me — "Kira, wait!"
        I keep walking.

        Florence's chamber is still sparse and isolated. When I arrive, she's positioned near the small window opening, watching the eastern boundary.

        Florence observes without turning — "You can see the hostile plants gathering — they're forming assault positions, multiple approach vectors, coordinated timing — professional execution."

        I say — "We need your help."

        Florence's platform rotates slightly to face me.
        Florence says — "Do you? Or does Holloway need my help while resenting that fact?"

        I say — "Both — all of us need your help, whether we want to admit it or not."

        Florence — "I'm not welcome in the group anymore, Kira — the others made that very clear."

        I say — "People are about to get hurt — I'm about to be in real danger — does that matter more than what they said to you two days ago?"

        Florence is quiet for a long moment.
        ¶
        Florence — "That's not fair."

        I say — "None of this is fair — you lied to them, they exiled you, and now hostile plants are attacking and we're all going to suffer for it. Fair doesn't enter into the situation."

        Florence asks — "What exactly are you asking me to do?"

        I say — "Come back — provide tactical guidance — help us defend the facility."

        Florence — "And after? When the attack is over and I'm not immediately useful anymore?"

        I admit — "I don't know — but right now we need you, and you're the only one who can help us survive this."

        Florence looks back toward the window.
        Florence — "They won't listen to me — they don't trust my judgment."

        I say — "They'll listen if the alternative is losing."

        Florence — "Will they? Or will they let pride override survival instinct?"

        That's a fair question — I don't have a good answer.

        I say — "Holloway is trying — really trying to coordinate defense — but tactical thinking isn't their specialty. They're assigning people to positions based on vague principles, not actual strategy — we're going to lose if you don't help."

        Florence — "And if I do help, if my guidance saves everyone, will they thank me? Forgive me? Or resent that they needed me?"

        I say honestly — "Probably the last one — at least at first."

        Florence makes a sound like rustling leaves — maybe a laugh.
        Florence — "You're very honest."

        I say — "You were honest too — eventually — about what you did and why. They didn't want to hear it, but you told them anyway."

        Florence — "And look where that got me."

        I say — "It got you isolated but alive — which is better than integrated but destroyed by hostile plants."

        Another long silence.
        ¶
        I add — "Please — I know they hurt you — I know you have every right to be angry and resentful — but I'm asking anyway: help us survive this."

        Florence turns fully to face me.
        Florence — "Why do you care? You're not a plant — this isn't your conflict."
      </text>
