        I say — "I live here."

        "These plants have been trying to keep me alive even when they don't know how. They care about me even though I'm different, even though helping me is complicated. And they're about to be attacked because they let me stay. So yes, this is my conflict."

        Scout bounces — emphatic agreement.

        Florence looks at Scout, then back to me. Florence says — "If I help — and I'm not saying I will — but if I help, it's because you're asking. Not them. You."

        I say — "I'll take that."

        She is quiet for a moment.

        ¶

        Florence asks — "What are they doing wrong?"

        I say — "Everything. Holloway's assigning defensive positions based on 'everyone stand near something and defend it.' No cohesive strategy, no coordination between defenders, no plan for what happens when the attack actually comes."

        Florence makes a disapproving sound. Florence says — "Typical. They're thinking about defense as a collection of individual actions, not as a coordinated system."

        I say — "So help me fix that."

        Florence repeats — "They won't listen to me."

        I say — "Then help me understand what needs to happen, and I'll tell them. Make me your proxy if you don't want to face them directly."

        Florence considers this. Florence says — "That could work. You give them tactical guidance — 'based on your human military knowledge' or some fiction like that. They listen because it's coming from you, not me."

        I suggest — "Or we could just be honest. Tell them the guidance is from you and they can take it or leave it. But at least give them the option."

        Florence, voice tinged with bitterness, says — "Honest. Because honesty worked so well for me before."

        I say — "It did, actually. They didn't like what you said, but they heard you. You told them the truth about what you did and why. Maybe they'll hear the truth about how to survive this too."

        Florence says — "You're more optimistic than I am."

        I say — "One of us has to be."

        Scout bounces — agreement, encouragement, hope.

        Florence looks between us. Florence says — "If I come back and they reject my guidance, if they let pride override survival, I'm returning here. I won't watch people get hurt because they're too stubborn to listen."

        I say — "Fair enough."

        Florence says — "And if we survive this, it doesn't mean automatic forgiveness. I'm still the one who lied to them. They're still the ones who exiled me. Those facts don't change."

        I say — "I know."

        Florence admits quietly — "But you're right that Kira being in danger matters more than my resentment. I can be angry about how they treated me _and_ help keep you alive. Both can be true."

        I agree — "Both *CAN* be true."

        Florence turns her platform toward the door. Florence says — "Let's go save everyone who hates me."

        I say — "They don't hate you."

        Florence asks — "Don't they?"

        I say — "They're hurt by you. There's a difference."

        Florence says — "Sometimes the difference doesn't matter much. But I suppose we'll find out."

        We head back toward the main facility. Scout bounces ahead — excited, worried, hopeful all at once.

        Behind us, through the window, the hostile plants continue gathering.

        The attack is coming.
      </text>
